    <!-- IRON DOSING GUIDE -->
    <div class="ing-box">
      <h4>Iron Dosing Guide: How Much Elemental Iron Do You Actually Need?</h4>
      <p>Iron requirements vary dramatically by age, sex, diet, and life stage. Understanding your specific needs prevents both deficiency and unnecessary excess — because unlike water-soluble vitamins, iron accumulates in the body and excess iron causes oxidative damage to organs.</p>

      <div class="vs-strip">
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>8mg/day — Adult Men & Postmenopausal Women</strong>
          <p>The baseline requirement for adults without menstrual iron losses. Most men and postmenopausal women meet this through diet alone and do not need iron supplementation unless blood tests confirm deficiency. Routine iron supplementation without documented need is not recommended for this group.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>15mg/day — Adolescent Girls (14-18)</strong>
          <p>The combination of rapid growth and menstruation onset creates elevated iron requirements. Dietary surveys consistently show that 75% of teenage girls in the US do not meet the iron RDA through food alone, making this demographic one of the highest-risk groups for iron depletion.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>18mg/day — Menstruating Women (19-50)</strong>
          <p>Double the requirement of adult men due to menstrual blood losses averaging 30-40mL per cycle. Women with heavy periods, IUD users (copper IUDs increase bleeding), and those on restricted diets are at highest risk. This is the target dose for most iron gummy users.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>27mg/day — Pregnant Women</strong>
          <p>The highest iron requirement of any demographic, driven by 50% expansion of maternal blood volume, placental development, and fetal iron needs. Most iron gummies provide only 10-18mg per serving, so pregnant women with low ferritin typically need prescription iron supplementation under physician supervision.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="warn-box">
        <div class="warn-box-ico"><Icon name="warning" size={18} /></div>
        <p><strong>Iron toxicity is real — do not oversupplement:</strong> Unlike vitamin C or B vitamins, excess iron accumulates in the body and causes oxidative damage to the liver, heart, and pancreas. Iron overload (hemochromatosis) affects approximately 1 in 200 people of Northern European descent. Never take iron supplements without first confirming deficiency through a blood test (serum ferritin + CBC). The Tolerable Upper Intake Level for iron is 45mg per day for adults.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

