    <div class="tested-box">
      <h3>How We Tested These Iron Gummies</h3>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Purchased independently.</strong> All 8 iron gummies were purchased at full retail price through Amazon. No brand was notified of this evaluation, and no products were received as samples or at discounted rates.</li>
        <li><strong>Verified iron form and elemental dose.</strong> We confirmed the specific iron form (bisglycinate, fumarate, or plant-derived) and calculated the elemental iron content per serving. Some supplement facts panels list the total weight of the iron compound rather than elemental iron — we verified the actual iron content consumers will absorb.</li>
        <li><strong>Tested GI tolerability.</strong> Six panel members with documented iron sensitivity (history of GI side effects from ferrous sulfate) used each product for 2 weeks and rated gastrointestinal comfort on a standardized 1-10 scale. Products were tested in randomized order with 1-week washout periods.</li>
        <li><strong>Assessed absorption enhancers.</strong> We evaluated whether each product includes vitamin C (the most evidence-based iron absorption enhancer) and at what dose, and whether any ingredients present could inhibit iron absorption (calcium, polyphenols).</li>
        <li><strong>Reviewed third-party certifications.</strong> We contacted manufacturers for certificates of analysis and prioritized products with USP Verification, NSF certification, USDA Organic, or Non-GMO Project Verified status over generic "third-party tested" claims.</li>
        <li><strong>Calculated cost-effectiveness.</strong> We computed the cost per milligram of elemental iron, factoring in bioavailability differences between iron forms. A 10mg bisglycinate serving with 3x absorption efficiency is more cost-effective than an 18mg fumarate serving, even if the per-serving price is identical.</li>
      </ol>
