    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Iron Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do iron gummies work as well as iron pills?</summary>
      <p>Iron gummies can be effective for maintaining adequate iron levels and correcting mild deficiency, but they typically contain lower elemental iron per serving (10-18mg) compared to prescription iron tablets (65-100mg elemental iron). However, ferrous bisglycinate — the form used in most iron gummies — has 2-4 times higher bioavailability than ferrous sulfate tablets, partially compensating for the lower dose. For moderate to severe iron deficiency anemia (ferritin below 15 ng/mL), your physician may recommend higher-dose prescription iron. For daily maintenance and mild deficiency, iron gummies provide adequate elemental iron with significantly better GI tolerance.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Why do iron supplements cause stomach pain?</summary>
      <p>Traditional iron supplements use ferrous sulfate, which dissociates in the stomach into free iron ions that irritate the gastric mucosa. This causes nausea, cramping, constipation, and dark stools in approximately 30-50% of users. Iron gummies solve this by using chelated iron forms like ferrous bisglycinate, where the iron atom is bonded to the amino acid glycine. The chelate passes through the stomach intact and absorbs in the small intestine through amino acid pathways, avoiding the free radical generation that causes GI distress.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much iron do women need daily?</summary>
      <p>The RDA varies significantly by life stage. Adult women aged 19-50 need 18mg per day — double the 8mg for men — because of menstrual iron losses. Pregnant women require 27mg daily. After menopause, women need only 8mg. Vegetarian and vegan women should aim for 1.8 times the RDA (32mg) because plant-based non-heme iron has lower bioavailability than heme iron from animal sources. Most iron gummies provide 10-18mg per serving, covering the daily RDA for menstruating women.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take iron gummies with vitamin C?</summary>
      <p>Yes, and it is strongly recommended. Vitamin C significantly enhances non-heme iron absorption by reducing ferric iron (Fe3+) to ferrous iron (Fe2+), the absorbable form. Research shows that 100mg of vitamin C taken with iron increases absorption by up to 67%. Several iron gummies in our guide already include vitamin C. If yours does not, take it with orange juice or a vitamin C supplement. Avoid taking iron with calcium, coffee, tea, or dairy, as these inhibit absorption.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is ferrous bisglycinate and why is it better?</summary>
      <p>Ferrous bisglycinate is a chelated iron form where one iron atom is bonded to two glycine molecules. It absorbs through amino acid transport pathways (PEPT1) rather than the standard DMT1 iron transporter, providing 2-4 times higher bioavailability than ferrous sulfate at equivalent doses. The chelation prevents free iron from reacting with stomach tissue, eliminating the nausea, constipation, and cramping that make traditional iron supplements intolerable for many users.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What are the symptoms of iron deficiency?</summary>
      <p>Iron deficiency progresses through three stages. Stage 1 (depletion): ferritin below 30 ng/mL with subtle fatigue. Stage 2 (iron-deficient erythropoiesis): ferritin below 15 ng/mL with noticeable fatigue, brain fog, cold extremities, brittle nails, and restless legs. Stage 3 (anemia): hemoglobin below 12 g/dL in women, causing severe fatigue, pallor, shortness of breath, rapid heartbeat, and pica (cravings for ice or non-food items). Iron deficiency is the most common nutritional deficiency worldwide, affecting 1.6 billion people.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Should I take iron gummies on an empty stomach?</summary>
      <p>For maximum absorption, iron is traditionally recommended on an empty stomach — 1 hour before or 2 hours after a meal. However, chelated iron forms used in gummies are less affected by food inhibitors than ferrous sulfate. If empty-stomach iron causes discomfort, taking it with a small amount of vitamin C-rich food (orange juice, strawberries) maintains good absorption while reducing irritation. Avoid taking iron with calcium, coffee, tea, or dairy products, which significantly inhibit absorption.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How long does it take for iron gummies to raise ferritin?</summary>
      <p>With consistent daily supplementation of 10-18mg elemental iron, most individuals see improved energy within 2-4 weeks as hemoglobin begins to rise. Serum ferritin typically requires 3-6 months to normalize from depleted levels. Complete iron repletion to a target ferritin of 50-100 ng/mL may take 6-12 months with gummy-level doses. A CBC and ferritin blood test at 3 months is recommended to assess progress. If ferritin has not increased after 3 months, consult your physician to evaluate for underlying causes.</p>
    </details>

